MatchedObjectDescriptor.QualificationSummary:
Although a specific length of time and experience is not required for most trade and labor occupations, you must show through experience and training that you possess the quality level of knowledge and skill necessary to perform the duties of the position at the level for which you are applying. Qualification requirements emphasis is on quality of experience, not necessarily the length of time. Your qualifications will be evaluated on the basis of your level of knowledge, skills, abilities and/or competencies in the job elements and screen out listed below. This job has a screen-out element which will be used to determine minimum eligibility for this job. Applicants who do not receive a minimum of two points on the screen-out element(s) will be found ineligible. The Screen-out Element for this position is: ABILITY TO DO THE WORK OF THE POSITION WITHOUT MORE THAN NORMAL SUPERVISION 1) Troubleshooting, evaluating, modifying, and maintaining advanced composite components;
2) Fabricating and repairing various aircraft sheet metal, reinforced plastic, fiberglass, and composite structures and component parts as needed for the repair of crash damage, modification, or overhaul;
3) Removing and installing materials associated with maintaining a Low Observable (LO) system;
4) Working with computer documentation and signature assessment systems used to track LO system health and maintenance;
5) Reading and working with blueprints, process specifications, engineering directives, technical directives, and all other technical data related to F-35 aircraft maintenance. Applicants must meet the requirements of the Office of Personnel Management (OPM) Job Qualification Handbook for Trades and Labor Occupations. Additional qualification information can be found at: https://www.opm.gov/policy-data-oversight/classification-qualifications/federal-wage-system-qualifications/#url=List-of-Approved-Job-Elements Experience refers to paid and unpaid experience, including volunteer work done through National Service programs (e.g., professional, philanthropic, religious, spiritual, community, student, social). Volunteer work helps build critical competencies, knowledge, and skills and can provide valuable training and experience that translates directly to paid employment.
